    "summary": "The Battle of Kulikovo (September 8, 1380 AD) was the most celebrated Russian military victory of the medieval period, in which Grand Prince Dmitri Ivanovich of Moscow (thereafter known as Dmitri Donskoi, 'of the Don') led a coalition of Russian princes against the Mongol commander Mamai's [[event:2305|Golden Horde]] army at Kulikovo Field on the Don River, defeating it in a hard-fought battle that became the founding myth of Russian national resistance and the symbol of the eventual end of the 'Tatar Yoke.' The victory did not immediately end Mongol suzerainty — Moscow was sacked by Khan Tokhtamysh just two years later — but its psychological significance was enormous.\n\nThe battle is described in considerable detail in the 'Tale of the Battle of Mamaev' and other Russian chronicles, which may contain legendary elements but give a vivid picture of the engagement. The Russian army reportedly received a blessing from St. Sergius of Radonezh — the greatest Russian saint of the medieval period — whose endorsement conferred both spiritual legitimacy and morale. The Russian forces used an ambush of concealed cavalry that struck Mamai's flank at the decisive moment, turning the battle. Mamai fled and was later killed by Tokhtamysh. The battle demonstrated that Russian forces could defeat a major Mongol army in open battle — a revelation with profound psychological consequences — and Dmitri's victory earned him the honorific 'Donskoi' (of the Don). Kulikovo is celebrated annually in Russia as a national holiday, and its battlefield has been designated a national historical site.",
